Consider a test mass&nbsp;\(m\)&nbsp;being moved away from a planet.<br><ol><li>To move&nbsp;\(m\)&nbsp;a small distance&nbsp;\(\Delta r\)&nbsp;in the&nbsp;<b>opposite direction of gravitational force</b>&nbsp;\(F_\text{grav}\).</li><li>Its GPE is increased by an&nbsp;<b>equal and opposite force</b>&nbsp;\(F\)&nbsp;acting through a distance&nbsp;\(\Delta r\), and</li><li>By an amount of energy&nbsp;<b>equal to the work done</b>&nbsp;by&nbsp;\(F\)\[\Delta W=F\Delta r\]</li><li>The&nbsp;<b>change of potential</b>&nbsp;of the test mass&nbsp;\(\Delta V=\frac{F\Delta r}{m}\)<br></li><li>So&nbsp;\(F=\frac{m\Delta V}{\Delta r}\)</li><li>So&nbsp;\(F_\text{grav}=-\frac{m\Delta V}{\Delta r}\)</li><li>So&nbsp;\(g=\frac{F_\text{grav}}{m}=-\frac{\Delta V}{\Delta r}\)</li></ol>